commitResults.messageBody:
Parser does not allow for variable number of arguments.

This prevents edit/search commands from being meaningful.

Let's,
- Allow Parser to parse variable number of arguments
- Make arguments order-insensitive for user convenience

Note that JUnit assertEquals() calls the Object's equal() method for
comparison.

Let's add equals() to AddCommand() and Item().

This will also be done for future CommandParser tests.

commitResults.messageBody:
The code was not very readable.

Optionals were used to distinguish between compulsory and optional
arguments.

Let's
- use Optionals to represent commands that are not needed
- Rework the relevant code to make them work with Optionals

Add case-insensitive search to SearchCommand Add extra comments and extracted magic strings
commitResults.messageBody:
SearchCommand does case-sensitive search.

A case insensitve search would be more user friendly since users cannot
be expected to remember exact cases of keywords.

Let's update the search algorithm to use case-insensitive matching

Also, some comments and magic strings were extracted for better clarity.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix name matching bug in SearchCommand

commitResults.messageBody:
SearchCommand matched whole words when searching.

Let's change the implementation that will be similar to Java's
String.contains(). In other words, the search term does not need to
match a whole word.

commitResults.messageBody:
ItemList used ArrayList<> previously.

This is a mutable collection.

For testing, we would like to have immutable collections.

Let's
- Change ArrayList to List
- Change the relevant code to match syntax
- Add immutable lists for test stubs

commitResults.messageTitle: Add detailed toString method for Item()
commitResults.messageBody:
Item currently only has a single toString() method, which prints name and quantity.

We may want different interpretations of Item in differente contexts, e.g. Edit and Search

Let's
- Create a toDetailedString() in Item
- Change the implementation accordingly in Edit and Search to use toDetailedString

Previously, SearchCommand used its output for JUnit tests.

It is not very robust.

A List<Item> results is implemented instead to represent the returned items for commands that do not modify ItemList. Examples are list and search.

More tests could be done to verify the printing functionality. However, the new implementation suffices in checking that the order of selected Items are correct.

Let's
- Create a List<Item> results in the base Command.class
- Change SearchCommand tests to check against this results list.

commitResults.messageBody:
AddCommand Class is a subclass of Command Class, created only when a
user uses the keyword "add" at the front of his input.

AddCommand will converse with ItemList to add an item into the itemList
attribute, and will then converse with Ui to show an output.

Resolves: #8

DeleteCommand Class is a subclass of Command Class, created only when a
user uses the keyword "delete" at the front of his input.

DeleteCommand will converse with ItemList to remove an item from the
itemList attribute, and will then converse with Ui to show an output.

Resolves: #10
